Vis 1 Distribution of Genre

First, look at the general distribution of movie generes.

ggplot(movie, aes(genre))+
  geom_bar(aes(fill=genre))+
  labs(title="Movie by Genre")

Next, I want to take a look at the change of movie genres throughout the time.

ggplot(movie, aes(year)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=genre)) 
## Warning: position_stack requires non-overlapping x intervals

By looking at the graph, there is a clear outliker year before 1920. So let’s try get rid of the outlier.

genre<-subset(movie, year>1920)
ggplot(genre, aes(year)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=genre))+
  labs(title="Movie Genre")
## Warning: position_stack requires non-overlapping x intervals

Even in the new graph, data points before 1990 are very limited compared to the time afterwards. So we focus on movie genres after 1990 to see the pattern.

genre<-subset(movie, year>1990)
ggplot(genre, aes(year)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=genre))+
  labs(title="Movie Genre")
## Warning: position_stack requires non-overlapping x intervals

The pattern is not very clear, in some years there were few movies in the data set. But the numbers of action movies and short movies are generally stable.

Vis 2 Relationships between Movie Ratings and Earnings

The following charts show the relationships between IMDb ratings and rating with worldwide earnings,respectively.

ggplot(movie, aes(rating,Worldwide)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + 
  ggtitle("Relationship between Rating and Worldwide Earnings") +
  labs(x="Rating", y="Worldwide Earnings")

ggplot(movie, aes(IMDb_rating,Worldwide)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + 
  ggtitle("Relationship between IMDb Rating and Worldwide Earnings") +
  labs(x="IMDb Rating", y="Worldwide Earnings")

In generally, there is no significant relationship betwwen movie ratings and earnings. And it is intersting that based on linear regression, there is a negative ralationship between movie ratings and earnings. Therefore, we can infer that high ratings are not guaranteed for good box office. IMDb rating is viewed more as reflecting professional views, which might not be in line with audiance’ preference.

Vis 3 Movie Earnings by Genres

ggplot(movie, aes(genre, Worldwide))+
  geom_boxplot() + labs(title = "Worldwide Movie Earnings by Genres", y = "Worldwide Earnings", x = "Move Genre")+
  coord_flip()+
  theme_classic()

Earnings of dramas and romance movies vary the most. And there are two action movies and 1 short movies that had substantially high earnings.

Vis 4 Domestic Earnings and Internaitonal Earnings

ggplot(movie, aes(Domestic,International)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method="lm") + 
  ggtitle("Relationship between Domestic and International Earnings") +
  labs(x="Domestic Earnings", y="International Earnings")

There is a clear positive relationship between movies’ domestic and international earnings. So good movies are generally well received even across different cultures.
